# Android SDK Conventions

## Tech Stack

Kotlin, OpenTelemetry Android SDK, Gradle (multi-module), min API 21

## Project Structure

```
pulse-android-otel/
├── android-agent/           # Main agent (assembles all instrumentations)
├── core/                    # OpenTelemetry RUM core
├── common/                  # Shared utilities
├── services/                # Internal services (network, periodic work)
├── session/                 # Session management
├── pulse-android-sdk/       # Public API (PulseSDK)
├── pulse-android-sdk-internal/ # Internal SDK implementation details
├── pulse-semconv/           # Pulse semantic conventions (attribute keys)
├── pulse-utils/             # Utilities (toAttributes, toMap, etc.)
├── pulse-sampling/          # Sampling logic (models/, core/, remote/)
├── pulse-upload-plugin/     # Gradle plugin for source map uploads
├── instrumentation/         # Instrumentation modules (see below)
├── demo-app/                # Demo application
├── test-common/             # Shared test utilities
└── buildSrc/                # Shared Gradle convention plugins
```

## Instrumentation Modules

All instrumentations live under `instrumentation/`. Two layout patterns:

**Flat modules** (simple, single `build.gradle.kts`):
`activity/`, `fragment/`, `anr/`, `crash/`, `network/`, `slowrendering/`, `sessions/`, `startup/`, `view-click/`, `compose/click/`

**Multi-submodule** (complex instrumentations):

| Module | Submodules | Pattern |
|--------|------------|---------|
| `okhttp3/`, `okhttp3-websocket/`, `httpurlconnection/`, `android-log/` | `library/`, `agent/`, `testing/` | Runtime / build-time / tests |
| `interaction/` | `core/`, `library/`, `remote/` | Business logic / OTel integration / API client |
| `location/` | `core/`, `library/`, `models/`, `processors/` | Provider / OTel integration / data / attribute appenders |

New instrumentations should follow the flat pattern unless they need build-time bytecode instrumentation (use `library/agent/testing`) or have distinct core logic and API clients (use `core/library/remote`).

## Package Naming

Two package roots — never mix them:

- `io.opentelemetry.android.*` — OTel-upstream code (instrumentations, session, internal services)
- `com.pulse.*` — Pulse-specific code (SDK API, semantic conventions, sampling, utilities)

## Gradle Conventions

- All library modules apply `otel.android-library-conventions` and `otel.publish-conventions` from `buildSrc/`
- `settings.gradle.kts` uses `includeFromDir("instrumentation")` to auto-discover modules up to 3 levels deep
- Typical module depends on `projects.instrumentation.commonApi`, `projects.instrumentation.androidInstrumentation`, `projects.services`, `projects.session`, `projects.common`

## File & Class Naming

| Type | Convention | Examples |
|------|------------|---------|
| Instrumentation classes | `*Instrumentation` | `ActivityLifecycleInstrumentation`, `OkHttpInstrumentation` |
| Support classes | `*Tracker`, `*Tracer`, `*Listener`, `*Manager`, `*Provider`, `*Appender`, `*Extractor` | `SessionManager`, `ActivityTracer`, `SlowRenderListener` |
| Test classes | `*Test.kt` | `InteractionManagerTest.kt` |
| File naming | One top-level class per file; filename matches class name | `SessionManager.kt` → `class SessionManager` |

## Discovery & Registration

All instrumentations use `@AutoService(AndroidInstrumentation::class)` for automatic discovery — no manual registration needed.

## Visibility

- `public` for SDK API surface (`PulseSDK`, `AndroidInstrumentation` interface)
- `internal` for module-internal code that should not leak to consumers
- `@JvmOverloads` / `@JvmStatic` where Java interop is needed

## Extension Functions

Shared extensions live in `pulse-utils` (`com.pulse.otel.utils`):
- `Map<String, Any?>.toAttributes()` / `Attributes.toMap()`
- `AttributesBuilder putAttributesFrom Map` (infix)

## Companion Object Patterns

- Constants: `companion object { const val INSTRUMENTATION_NAME = "..." }`
- Singletons: `PulseSDK.INSTANCE` via `by lazy`
- Factory methods: `NetworkDetector.create(context)`

## Span Types (`pulse.type`)

- `interaction` — critical user interaction spans
- `screen_session` / `screen_load` — screen tracking
- `app_start` — cold/warm start
- `device.anr` / `device.crash` / `non_fatal` — stability events
- `app.jank.frozen` / `app.jank.slow` — rendering performance
- `network.<status>` / `network.change` — network calls and connectivity
- `session.start` / `session.end` — session boundaries
- `custom_event` — developer-defined events
- `app.click` — touch/click events

## Span Attributes

Use `pulse.*` prefixed attributes for Pulse-specific data:
- `pulse.type` — categorizes the span (see list above)
- `pulse.interaction.name` — critical interaction name
- `pulse.interaction.id`, `pulse.interaction.apdex_score`, `pulse.interaction.user_category`
- `screen.name`, `last.screen.name` — screen identifiers
- `app.interaction.frozen_frame_count`, `app.interaction.slow_frame_count` — rendering metrics
- `pulse.session.anr.count`, `pulse.session.crash.count` — session-level stability counters

## Resource Attributes

- `app.build_name` — app version (materialized as `AppVersion` in ClickHouse)
- `os.name` — platform (materialized as `Platform`)
- `os.version` — OS version (materialized as `OsVersion`)
- `device.model.name` — device model (materialized as `DeviceModel`)
- `rum.sdk.version` — SDK version

## Best Practices

- No wildcard imports
- Group imports by source (stdlib, Android, OTel, project)
- Prefer `internal` for non-API classes
- Use `@AutoService` for all new instrumentations
- Keep one top-level class per file (test helper classes are an exception)

## Publishing

Automated via `.github/workflows/publish-android.yml`

## Code Style

Follow Kotlin conventions — `camelCase` for functions/properties, `PascalCase` for classes. Formatting enforced by Spotless (`otel.spotless-conventions`).
